\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Social Polarization in Response to Contagions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
I construct a very simple utility-based model of social connections which
 leads to variation in the number of social connections each person has.
 When the threat of a contagion is introduced, highly connected individuals
 have less incentive to break off marginal social connections than do less
 connected individuals.
 This increases the variance of the distribution of connections, which has
 important implications in understanding the spread of contagions such as
 disease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why does it seem that some highly secluded people with very low exposure
 risk are highly concerned about social distancing, while other more gregarious
 individuals at very high risk of exposure don't seem to care at all?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the personal risk from a contagion is the same for two individuals, then
 an individual with a very high number of social connections expects to
 almost certainly be exposed to the contagion regardless of any marginal
 changes they make to their behavior.
 But for an individual with very few connections, slight changes in their
 behavior can drastically reduce their disease risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I construct the simplest model which I can think of that results in individuals
 choosing to have different numbers of social connections.
 Then when the threat of of contagion is introduced, the risk to an individual
 comes from their neighbors, but this risk is spread out in a non-linear
 way.
 The very first neighbor provides the highest expected risk of contagion,
 and subsequent neighbors provide exponentially decreasing expected disease
 exposure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of this, the variation and spread of a disease 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A simple model of endogenous social connections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I make assumptions about the utility of maintaining social connections,
 and about the disutility of being exposed to contagion, such that individuals
 with lots of neighbors are precisely those who won't decide to socially
 distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Social Connections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a unit mass of individuals, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from 0 to 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each person 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 has some randomly determined exogenous level of social skill or social
 capital 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Social capital follows a gamma distribution with shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\kappa}(\kappa_{x})=\frac{\kappa_{x}^{k-1}e^{-\kappa_{x}/\theta_{\kappa}}}{\Gamma(k)\theta_{\kappa}^{k}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\kappa}(\kappa_{x})=\frac{\gamma(k,\frac{\kappa_{x}}{\theta_{\kappa}})}{\Gamma(k)}=\frac{\int_{0}^{\kappa_{x}/\theta_{\kappa}}t^{k-1}e^{-t}\;dt}{\int_{0}^{\infty}t^{k-1}e^{-t}\;dt}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each person chooses what level of 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

 social connections they wish to maintain, and uses this connection with
 others to improve their own welfare.
 These connections could be thought of employment which allows the person
 to buy goods, agreements with neighbors to cooperate on home-production
 activities like childcare, or intrinsically rewarding social interactions
 like friendships and dance partners.
 Higher levels of social capital enable a person to get more utility out
 of each connection, but there are diminishing returns to seeking out new
 connections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility that person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, with social capital 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}$
\end_inset

, gains from choosing to maintain 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 connections is 
\begin_inset Formula $A\kappa_{x}^{\alpha}n^{1-\alpha}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are parameters common across all people.
 Here, a person can only choose how much they interact with others and cannot,
 for example, choose to only connect with other people who have low social
 capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maintenance of each unit of social connection requires effort which
 incurs exogenous disutility 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

's utility as a function of their choice of social connections is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{x}(n)=A\kappa_{x}^{\alpha}n^{1-\alpha}-\varpi n
\]

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{x}=n(\kappa_{x})$
\end_inset

 denotes person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

's optimal amount of social connections, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{x}=n(\kappa_{x})=\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\kappa_{x}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{x}=n^{-1}(n_{x})=\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}n_{x}
\]

\end_inset

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $n(\kappa_{x})$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing and differentiable over the support for the distribution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, we can relate the two density functions like so:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{N}(n_{x}) & =f_{\kappa}\left(n^{-1}(n_{x})\right)\cdot\frac{\partial}{\partial n_{x}}n^{-1}(n_{x})\\
 & =f_{\kappa}\left(\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}n_{x}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I was thinking about trying to generalize and simplify this using pgfs,
 but then remembered that these will be continuous instead of discrete.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then because a person's social connections will be a constant multiple of
 their social capital, we'll find that social connections are also gamma-distrib
uted with the same shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and with scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}\equiv\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\theta_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{N}(n_{x}) & =f_{\kappa}\left(\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}n_{x}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}\\
 & =\left[\frac{1}{\Gamma(k)}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{\kappa}}\right)^{k}\cdot\left(\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}n_{x}\right)^{k-1}\cdot\exp\left(-\frac{\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}n_{x}}{\theta_{\kappa}}\right)\right]\cdot\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\Gamma(k)}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{\kappa}}\right)^{k}\left(\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}\right)^{k}\cdot n_{x}^{k-1}\cdot\exp\left(-\frac{\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{-1}{\alpha}}n_{x}}{\theta_{\kappa}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{\Gamma(k)}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{\kappa}\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}}\right)^{k}\cdot n_{x}^{k-1}\cdot\exp\left(-\frac{n_{x}}{\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\theta_{\kappa}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{n_{x}^{k-1}e^{-n_{x}/\left[\theta_{\kappa}\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\right]}}{\Gamma(k)\left[\theta_{\kappa}\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\right]^{k}}\\
 & =\frac{n_{x}^{k-1}e^{-n_{x}/\theta_{n}}}{\Gamma(k)\theta_{n}^{k}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Increasing the cost of socializing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi$
\end_inset

 decreases the scale parameter in the distribution of social contacts.
 The mean number of contacts is 
\begin_inset Formula $k\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

 and the variance is 
\begin_inset Formula $k\theta_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So mean and standard deviation will scale by the same amount.
 Neat.
 Will that mean the expected number of infections decreases by the same
 amount as well? I'll have to seeee.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Individual Transmission of a Contagion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is some contagion which spreads through social connections in an SIR
 manner.
 Like in (Newman 2002) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-9"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which provides a general description of evaluating the spread of disease
 through a network, I'm considering the spread of the epidemic by looking
 at it's final outcomes rather than by looking at the time-path of infectious
 frequency among the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose for now the that the above pattern of social connections is retained
 throughout the epidemic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 denote the transmissibility of the contagion.
 It is the chance that an infected person will transmit the disease to an
 uninfected person given that they share a social connection.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Contrast 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

, the basic reproduction number, which is the average number of new infections
 generated by each infection when the entire population is initial susceptible.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

 is determined by a combination of the transmission rate and structure of
 social interactions.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-8"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 here is the same for all connections between people.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 becomes infected, how many times can they be expected to transmit the disease
 to others? If they have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{x}$
\end_inset

 units of social connection, and have an iid chance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of transmitting the contagion per unit of social connection, then the answer
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $rn_{x}$
\end_inset

 on average.
 Call this 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}\equiv rn_{x}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
individual reproductive number
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, to borrow a term from (Lloyd-Smith, Schreiber, Kopp, Getz 2005) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number of transmissions from person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 draws from a 
\begin_inset Formula $Poisson(v_{x})$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 And because this is a multiple of the person's social connections, these
 individual reproductive numbers will also be gamma-distributed across the
 population, with the same shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{v}\equiv r\theta_{n}=r\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\theta_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{v}(v_{x})=\frac{v_{x}^{k-1}e^{-v_{x}/\theta_{v}}}{\Gamma(k)\theta_{v}^{k}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean of this distribution gives us the mean secondary attack rate across
 a susceptible population: 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{0}=\theta_{v}k=k\cdot r\left(\frac{A\cdot(1-\alpha)}{\varpi}\right)^{\frac{1}{\alpha}}\theta_{\kappa}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and variance=
\begin_inset Formula $k\theta_{v}^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Something about how this process is POisson for each person? 
